<Base title="Down the Banksy Is Apparently Wirral-Curious | Down the Banksy | Blind Ant" description="A Down the Banksy wall text on pricing the costs of both approving and refusing a carbon capture pipeline." type="Article">
  <h1>Down the Banksy is apparently Wirral-curious.</h1>

  <p>She came over to see her mate Charlotte Joanne, had one look at the carbon capture row, and started muttering about missing invoices.</p>

  <p>So, here’s the wall version:</p>

  <p>“NO IS NOT FREE.<br />YES IS NOT FREE EITHER.<br />PRICE BOTH COLUMNs.”</p>

  <p>I am not pro-pipeline by default. I live on the Wirral. I’ve lived here almost all my life, and I will probably live here for the rest of it. If someone wants to run a major CO₂ pipeline through or near the place I call home, then yes, I want answers.</p>

  <p>Route. Safety. Wildlife. Emergency planning. Public money. Above-ground installations. Construction disruption. Long-term monitoring. Who profits. Who carries the risk.</p>

  <p>All of it.</p>

  <p>But I also want the other column priced.</p>

  <p>If the scheme is intended to capture millions of tonnes of CO₂ from cement and lime production, then the honest question is not only:</p>

  <p>What are the risks of doing this?</p>

  <p>It is also:</p>

  <p>What happens if we don’t?</p>

  <p>If the answer is that better, cheaper, safer, lower-carbon cement processes can replace the need for this infrastructure at the same scale and in the same timescale, brilliant. Show that case. I would much rather have the better answer.</p>

  <p>But if the answer is that the CO₂ simply goes into the atmosphere while everyone congratulates themselves for stopping the local pipeline, then that is not a free “no.”</p>

  <p>That is an invoice redirected to the climate.</p>

  <p>Calling captured CO₂“industrial waste” may be technically arguable, but if you don’t also say it is CO₂ that would otherwise enter the atmosphere, the public is not being given the full bill.</p>

  <p>Down the Banksy’s rule is simple:</p>

  <p>The powerful don’t get to hide the cost of yes.<br />The objectors don’t get to hide the cost of no.<br />Both columns. Every time.</p>

  <p>Not because pipelines are automatically good.</p>

  <p>Not because protest is automatically bad.</p>

  <p>Because public decisions should not be made with one eye covered and the other one full of slogans.</p>

  <p>PLANNING OBJECTION RECEIVED.<br />INVOICE REQUIRED FOR BOTH COLUMNS.a</p>

